==French==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|fr|abyme}} {{qualifier|archaic}}
* {{l|fr|abîme}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|fr}} {{term|abisme|lang=fro}} from {{etyl|LL.|fr}} {{term|*abyssimus|lang=la}}, a superlative of {{etyl|la|fr}} {{term|abyssus||bottomless pit|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|fr}} {{term|ἄβυσσος|lang=grc}}. Compare Spanish and Portuguese {{m|pt|abismo}}. Doublet of {{m|fr|abysse}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|Fr-abime-fr FR-Paris.ogg|Audio (Paris)|lang=fr}}

===Noun===
{{fr-noun|m}}

# [[abyss]], [[chasm]]
# [[bottom]] of a chasm or [[valley]]
# {{context|literary|lang=fr}} [[infiniteness]] of [[thought]]
# {{context|literary|lang=fr}} [[superlative]] used with various abstraction and qualities; the [[climax]] or [[acme]]
# {{context|literary|lang=fr}} [[hell]]
# {{context|heraldry|lang=fr}} [[abyss]] of a shield, [[fess point]]

====Usage notes====
* {{U:fr:1990 reform spelling}}
* Often used as if it was a [[pluralia tantum]].
* Unlike the English {{term|abyss|lang=en}}, {{term|abime|lang=fr}} is not the usual term for underwater abysses (the same term, {{term|abysse|lang=fr}}, exists in French), although it is used for them.

